The Performance Efficiency pillar.

Performance Efficiency is the pillar about delivering on your performance targets without overspending. The checklist.

Pick the right compute: Lambda for sporadic event work, Fargate for steady containers, E-C-2 for sustained or custom workloads, and Graviton, the m-six-g and c-seven-g families, for roughly twenty percent better price-performance on most x-eighty-six workloads. Pick the right data engine per access pattern: R-D-S or Aurora for O-L-T-P, DynamoDB for key-value at any scale, Redshift for the warehouse, S3 plus Athena for the ad-hoc lake, OpenSearch for search, and ElastiCache for hot data. Cache aggressively: CloudFront at the edge, ElastiCache near the application, and D-A-X in front of DynamoDB when latency demands it. Use asynchronous patterns: S-Q-S, S-N-S, EventBridge, and Step Functions to decouple latency-sensitive paths from slow downstream work. And use auto-scaling with cooldowns, scaling on the right metric, C-P-U, queue depth, or request count, tuned so it reacts without thrashing.

The design principles: democratise advanced technology by using managed services, go global in minutes, use serverless, experiment often, and match the technology to the workload with mechanical sympathy. The core move is to match the tool to the access pattern, which is the single most-tested idea on the exam. There's no universal best database or compute; there's only the best fit for this read-write shape, this latency target, and this scale. The cue: lowest latency, handle unpredictable spikes, or the right database for this access pattern, all point to this pillar.
